<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Export Promotion Program Said To Break GATT Rules </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Export Promotion Program Said To Break GATT Rules </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1904191794 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 15 Apr 
94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PY1904191794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Livia Ferrari] </F>
  [Text] The foreign trade promotion program proposed by the 
Ministry of Industry, Commerce and Tourism (MICT) does not take 
into account the international rules that were ratified in the 
Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs 
(GATT). 
  In the opinion of the Association of Brazilian Exporters 
(AEB), for this reason it will not be accepted by the 
multilateral trade organ. 
  The program provides for the creation of fiscal incentive 
mechanisms, which contradict the GATT Code of Subsidies. The 
third article of the Code condemns the creation of foreign trade 
incentives based on "export performance" [preceding two words in 
English]. Despite this, the MICT project foresees that in order 
to have the fiscal incentives approved, enterprises will take 
minimum export commitments. 
  The matter was analyzed yesterday during a meeting of AEB 
entrepreneurs, for whom the project must be subject to external 
auditing for evaluation of specific conflicts with GATT 
principles. 
  AEB President Marcus Vinicius Pratini de Moraes is concerned 
that the program proposed by the government -- despite the fact 
that it is more generalized than the previous one (described in 
Draft Bill No. 3721/93, which provided for incentives for 
automobile exports only) -- will artificially create unequal 
competition conditions for various industrial sectors. 
  Pratini de Moraes said: "The old Befiex (an export fiscal 
incentive program created by Pratini de Moraes himself, when he 
was minister of industry and commerce, during the Medici 
administration) was a good program, and fulfilled its objective 
more than 20 years ago." In his opinion, the best way to 
support Brazilian foreign trade is to eliminate the tax burden 
on exports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11251 </DOCNO>
