<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nation, Emigre Community Conference Begins </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nation, Emigre Community Conference Begins </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Robaina Opening Address </H4>

<F P=102> FL2204181794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2204181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passages within quotation marks are recorded] </F>
  [Excerpt] The conference on the Nation and the Emigre 
Community began this morning at the Convention Center with an 
opening address by Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina. There are 
200 emigre community representatives in attendance from 
approximately 40 countries. In addition to Robaina, the 
conference is also being chaired by Carlos Lage, secretary of 
the Council of Ministers; Ricardo Alarcon, president of the 
National Assembly of the People's Government; Abel Prieto, 
president of the National Union of Cuban Writers and Artists; 
and Sergio Corrieri, president of the Cuban Institute of 
Friendship with Peoples. Conference spokesman Miguel Alfonso and 
secretary Jose Cabanas are present. 
  For those familiar with three decades of pressures, threats, 
and aggressions, it is easy to understand the personal effort of 
many and the merit of your decision to not sell out to those who 
exerted pressures and threats to prevent this meeting: These 
were the exact words of Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina during 
a welcoming address to the conference participants on behalf of 
the Cuban Government. 
  In his address, Robaina stated that the presence in Havana 
of 
Cubans who live abroad is an indication of support and 
identification with the Cuban nation as well as a recognition of 
our government's valor in convening this conference in the midst 
of the pressing and urgent tasks Cuba faces today. 
  [Robaina] "You have arrived in Cuba in the midst of an 
exceptional period, when our people are making extraordinary 
efforts to heroically preserve the fatherland's independence and 
sovereignty, and the gigantic accomplishments of the Revolution. 
If we commit to this conference, it is because the subject 
deserves to see the beginning of a joint discussion aimed at 
making progress along the road to normalize ties between the 
nation and its emigre community." 
  The conference is taking place under the same conditions of 
abnormality, of a U.S. policy of hostility toward Cuba, which 
since the triumph of the Revolution have shaped the ties with 
the emigre community. 
  [Robaina] "The fact that we are here today in this room is 
not even remotely the result of a miracle or accident. It is 
above all the result of our maturity, strength, and 
independence, and also the result of a growing attitude of 
respect and understanding of a significant portion of the emigre 
community who identifies more each day with the vital interests 
of Cuba." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

