<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Polling Stations Open for Run-Off Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Polling Stations Open for Run-Off Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2404134494 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1307 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2404134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 24 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- The Salvadoran 
polling stations opened at 0700 local (1300 GMT) today so 2.5 
million voters can decide which, either the rightist candidate, 
Armando Calderon Sol, or the leftist candidate, Ruben Zamora, 
will be the next president of the Republic. 
  More than 1,000 foreign observers, most of them from the 
United Nations, are attending the procedures. In addition, some 
6,000 police are watching over this run-off election, which will 
close at 1700 local (2300 GMT). 
  The Supreme Electoral Tribunal, which was severely 
criticized 
for irregularities in the first round held on 20 March, in the 
past few hours assured the people that the electoral machine was 
operating smoothly. The leftists, however, have warned of the 
danger of "another fraud" in favor of Calderon Sol. 

</TEXT>

