<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Communications Services spokesman </F>
Jose Antonio Roche -- live or recorded] 
  [Text] [Unidentified announcer] Let us go to Jose Antonio 
Roche, of the Communications Services here in Cuba. Renzoli [not 
further identified] said, privately, that wild changes are being 
made here in all the nation's telephones. Good morning, Roche. 
  [Roche] Good morning. Well, with the objective of 
reorganizing the telephone network in the city of Havana so as 
to allow the possibility of increased numerical combinations, at 
the telephone exchange for those numbers that begin with a seven 
and have five digits, as of Friday 29 April, people will have to 
add an eight to the number, giving those numbers six digits. For 
example, the number 7-2020 will, as of Friday, become 78-2020. 
This measure is being taken by the telephone company to 
reorganize its boards [pizarras] here in the capital. 
  [Announcer] So, now you know. 
  [Roche] The phone numbers beginning with seven will, as of 
the 29th, have six digits. People must now add an eight after 
the initial seven. 

