<H3> <TI>   Source Denies Drug Trafficking Charge </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Source Denies Drug Trafficking Charge </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604004394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604004394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A source close to the Haitian Army denies the 
accusations brought against Haitian Police Chief Lieutenant 
Colonel Joseph Michel Francois. According to the charges, the 
police chief has allegedly supported a lucrative drug trade 
between Colombia and the United States, through Haiti. Gabriel 
Taboana, a former Colombian drug trafficker, asserted before the 
Drug Trafficking and Terrorism Subcommission that he met Michel 
Francois during a meeting with Pablo Escoblar in (?Colombia). 
Former Haitian President Prosper Avril also participated in that 
meeting. 
  The source, who wishes to remain anonymous, pointed out that 
Col. Francois' last trip took place in 1981 before... [pauses] 
after he was commissioned. He went to the United States for 
proficiency courses in security. Since then, he has never gone 
abroad. How can Taboana assert that he met Col. Francois in 
1984, our source wonders. Remember that upon Col. Francois' 
return, he was appointed to the Heavy Vehicles Corps of the 
presidential guard at the National Palace. 

</TEXT>

