<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Outlines `Dangers' of NAFTA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Outlines `Dangers' of NAFTA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2604033994 Paris AFP in Spanish 0056 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2604033994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Managua, Apr 22 (AFP) -- Nicaraguan Foreign Minister 
Ernesto Leal today outlined the dangers posed to the Central 
American economy by NAFTA, which was recently signed by the 
United States, Mexico, and Canada. 
  Speaking before the U.S.-Nicaraguan Chamber of Commerce, 
Leal 
said the privileged access of Mexican products to the United 
States places Central America at a disadvantage. In turn, he 
urged that "a transition period" of about three years be adopted 
to allow the region to concentrate on improving competitiveness 
while it adheres to NAFTA. 
  The minister recalled that the presidents of the region had 
met with President Bill Clinton in November 1993 and that they 
proposed that the region enter the treaty under the same terms 
received by Mexico. However, he noted that unfavorable 
conditions in Central America -- a postwar economy and a 
technological lag -- prevented the region from advancing at the 
same pace maintained by more developed countries. 
  Today, about 50 percent of Central America's exports, which 
amount to some $4.5 billion, are shipped to U.S. markets. 

</TEXT>

