<H3> <TI>   Legislative Assembly Approves Labor Code Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Legislative Assembly Approves Labor Code Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2304153894 San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish 1800 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2304153894 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "YSU Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] On Thursday, the Legislative Assembly approved 48 
reforms to the Labor Code. The reforms were agreed upon during 
the recent Forum for Economic and Social Consensus. It also 
approved the creation of a Higher Council of Labor and the 
prompt resumption of work at the Forum for Economic and Social 
Consensus to deal with several pending issues. 
  Deputies of the Political and Labor and Social Welfare 
Commissions issued the surprise approvals, which were in turn 
approved by all political sectors represented at the Assembly. 
The reforms recognize the existence of trade, business, 
industrial, and independent contractor unions. The Ministry of 
Labor will aid in forming these organizations. The unions will 
be prohibited from denying nonunion workers the right to 
employment, [forcibly] enrolling such workers in unions, or 
refusing them the right to resign from unions. There will be 
penalties for those who violate the code's provisions. 
  [San Salvador Radio Cadena YSU in Spanish at 1800 GMT on 22 
April reports that the National Peasant-Worker Union, UNOC, 
expressed its disagreement with some of the reforms. UNOC 
leaders believe "the Legislative Assembly has taken a step that 
may not prove very positive for the working class in general." 
They added that some of the reforms "are detrimental to worker 
interests." The reforms, they say, were hastily approved to 
meet "a requirement of the foreign trade authorities of the 
United States."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

