<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Candidate Receives Death Threat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Coalition Candidate Receives Death Threat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2404045294 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1828 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2404045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 23 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Today, the 
Salvadoran left-wing coalition described the death threats 
against Vice Presidential Candidate Franciso Lima as a "dirty" 
trick by the ruling ARENA [Nationalist Republican Alliance] 
party. Lima, who is 76 years old, said telephone calls had been 
received over the last few hours warning him of an attack on his 
home. 
  Lima and coalition presidential candidate Ruben Zamora said 
during a news conference that the calls were made to an office 
of the former Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN) 
guerrillas and to the home of party coordinator Shafik Handal. 
The vice presidential hopeful recalled that Jose Maria Mendez, a 
lawyer friend, was threatened a few months ago with an attack 
against his wife if he did not help convince Lima to give up his 
FMLN candidacy. 
  Lima, an attorney and successful businessman, expressed 
concern over these events, especially after the police increased 
his security because "if they are worried, it is only natural 
that I should be worried; it is me they want to see buried." 
  Ruben Zamora said that in addition to the threats against 
Lima, FMLN radio repeaters in San Salvador and the Chinchontepec 
Volcanoes were sabotaged over the last few days, which "does not 
contribute to the atmosphere of peace" that should prevail 
during the elections. Zamora, who is 52 years old, will compete 
for the presidency for the second time against the ruling ARENA 
party candidate. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

