<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electoral Tribunal Sets Liquor, Weapons Restrictions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Electoral Tribunal Sets Liquor, Weapons Restrictions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2504144394 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 23 
Apr 94 p A1 </F>

<F P=103> PA2504144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] A recent investigation carried out by LA ESTRELLA DE 
PANAMA disclosed that the Electoral Tribunal has determined that 
the sale of all alcoholic beverages and the use of firearms will 
be prohibited beginning 7 May. By mean of two decrees, the 
Electoral Tribunal established that all bars, nightclubs, and 
dance halls are to remain closed as of 1200 on Saturday, 7 May, 
until 1200 on 9 May. The sale of wine, beer, and other fermented 
beverages have also been banned during this 72-hour [as 
published] period. 
  With respect to the use of firearms, the Electoral Tribunal 
determined that private citizens are barred from carrying 
firearms from 8 May until after 9 May, with the exception of the 
police authorities who by virtue of their responsibilities are 
required to carry arms. The decree warns that any person caught 
violating these firearms restrictions will be penalized by 
having the weapons confiscated and being given fines ranging 
from 10 to 250 balboas. On the other hand, the Government and 
Justice Ministry decided to prohibit the importation of all 
hunting weapons between during the period 31 March and 31 May of 
the current year. 
  Individuals violating these decrees will remain in the 
custody of the National Police until 31 May 1994. These decrees 
are aimed at ensuring citizen's harmony as well as respect and 
order for the individual's constitutional rights during the 8 
May election process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

