<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signs Trade Promotion Accords </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Signs Trade Promotion Accords </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2604002194 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2604002194 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Flavio Figueiredo in Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] The Brazilian and Czech Governments today signed 
economic cooperation agreements to expand bilateral relations 
and promote trade between the two countries. 
  Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus said that in 1993 
Brazilian 
exports to the Czech Republic totaled $7 million while its 
imports totaled $5 million. Klaus said these amounts were small 
following the separation of the Czech and Slovak Republics and 
the economic reform the Czech Republic has been undergoing. 
  Under the agreements, the governments of Brazil and the 
Czech 
Republic commit themselves to increase trade and to diversify 
their export and import items. They also agreed to undertake a 
joint cooperation effort in the areas of machinery production 
and professional training. 
  During his visit to Brazil, Klaus is also conveying to 
Brazilian officials the experience earned by the Czech Republic 
in the area of privatization. The Czech Republic has had the 
most expeditious privatization process in history. As late as 
1989 nothing had been privatized in the Czech Republic, but 
today the private sector already accounts for two-thirds of the 
country's GDP. 

</TEXT>

