<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ipen Employees Reportedly Contaminated by Radiation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ipen Employees Reportedly Contaminated by Radiation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2604013394 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 23 Apr 94 
p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PY2604013394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sao Paulo -- The Sao Paulo State Attorney's Office 
will investigate charges that 11 members of the Institute for 
Nuclear and Energy Research (Ipen) in Sao Paulo have been 
contaminated by radioactive material while working at one of the 
Ipen laboratories, which is controlled by the National Nuclear 
Energy Commission (CNEN). The Association of Ipen Employees 
(Assipen) and the Federal Employees Union in Sao Paulo 
(Sindisef) have stated that the Ipen employees -- five women and 
six men who operated machinery at the pharmaceuticals laboratory 
-- were contaminated by breathing Iodine- 131. 
  Ipen employees' representatives have reported that the 
contamination was detected through tests last month. Assipen 
Director Claudio Manoel Constancio said that the employees had a 
hormonal dysfunction in their thyroid glands, and that some of 
them had nodules and cysts in their glands. According to 
Constancio, Iodine-131 causes thyroid hyperactivity. 
  CNEN Radioprotection Director Laercio Vinhas yesterday 
reported by fax that the thyroid dysfunctions detected in the 
employees have no relation whatsoever with their work at the 
laboratory and that this problem is detected in 3 percent of the 
overall population. Vinhas added that only seven workers, and 
not 11, have been given sick leave because medical literature 
does not prohibit people with thyroid dysfunctions from working 
with iodine mixtures. 
  The affected employees refused to comment on the issue and, 
according to the Assipen director, fear retaliation by the 
company. Constancio said that the CNEN and Ipen have maintained 
absolute secrecy about the subject. Prosecutors who work for 
the Job Accidents Division of the Attorney General's Office have 
already summoned the company's superintendent, Spero Penha 
Morato, to clarify the situation during a meeting to be held on 
2 May. 
  The employees' representatives want doctors and experts of 
the Fundacentro, an organization linked to the Labor Ministry 
that is responsible for controlling workers' health, to examine 
the Ipen facilities at the Sao Paulo University campus. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

