<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   EZLN Communique Lauds Peace Negotiator, Lifts Alert </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EZLN Communique Lauds Peace Negotiator, Lifts Alert </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2504171494 Mexico City LA JORNADA in Spanish 22 Apr 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> PA2504171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City LA JORNADA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Text of communique issued by the Clandestine Indian </F>
Revolutionary Committee-General Command of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army in the Chiapas State mountains of southeastern 
Mexico on 20 April] 
  [Text] Communique by the Clandestine Indian Revolutionary 
Committee-General Command (CCRI-GC) of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN], Mexico. 
  20 April 1994. 
  To the people of Mexico: 
  To all the peoples and governments of the world: 
  To the national and international media: 
  Brothers: 
  The CCRI-GC of the EZLN addresses you to point out the 
following: 
  First -- The EZLN acknowledges the honest and serious 
efforts by Manuel Camacho Solis, commissioner for Peace and 
Reconciliation in Chiapas, and mediator Bishop Samuel Ruiz to 
create favorable conditions that may lead to the continuation of 
the dialogue, the objective of which is to ensure a just and 
dignified peace. During the past days, the commissioner as well 
as the mediator have sought to solve several obstacles that 
block the peace process. The EZLN applauds the genuine 
disposition of these two Mexicans. 
  Second -- The EZLN applauds the release of several 
civilians, 
unfairly charged with being members of our troops, and sees this 
as a good sign leading to the continuation of the dialogue for a 
just and dignified peace. 
  Third -- In return, the CCRI-GC of the EZLN hereby orders 
the 
partial deactivation of the red alert in effect throughout its 
territory, and the return of part of its troops to their 
respective communities and ejidos as of 23 April 1994. 
  Fourth -- If this favorable climate to a dialogue continues, 
the EZLN will renew the consultation process with its grass 
roots as soon as possible, at regular intervals and beginning 
with those less vulnerable territories. 
  Fifth -- The EZLN reiterates its disposition to a true 
political solution to those just demands that motivates its 
struggle, and applauds the sincere efforts by the Mexican 
civilian society as well as all personalities to search for 
dignified solutions to crucial national problems through reason 
and not through force. 
  Continuing with our popular demands for liberty, justice 
democracy for all Mexicans. Liberty! Justice! Democracy! 
Respectfully: 
  [Signed] Clandestine Indian Revolutionary Committee -- EZLN 
General Command. General Headquarters. 
  [Issued] Southeastern Mexican mountains, Chiapas State, 
Mexico, [no date as published] April 1994. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

