<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1204203594 </F>
<F P=103> PA1204203594 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments through 19 April. 
  Finance Minister Cesar Robalino announced on 5 April that 
the 
government signed a letter of intent with the IMF according to 
which Ecuador agreed to reduce inflation to 20 percent by the 
end of 1994 and cut the fiscal deficit to 0.5 percent of GNP. 
The agreements are directed at renegotiating the county's 
$12.6-billion foreign debt and seeking new loans. (Mexico City 
NOTIMEX in Spanish 1844 GMT 5 Apr 94) 
  The Defense Ministry announced that routes and frequencies 
currently belonging to Ecuatoriana de Aviacion were ceded to 
several other companies on a temporary basis. Defense Minister 
Jose Gallardo said that "once the inactive airline resumes 
operations, the beneficiaries will relinquish the routes." 
(Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 5 Apr 94) 
  A recent government report states that foreign reserves 
increased 4.39 percent in March over the previous month. 
Reserves now total $1.331 billion. According to a Central Bank 
official, this represents an influx of $56 million. The 
official said that there is increased confidence in Ecuador's 
economic future following the recent implementation of 
government measures. (Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 
GMT 11 Apr 94) 
  Ecuador's international monetary reserves set a new internal 
record in March by totaling $1.3 billion, the 15th best 
registration since 13 years ago when the economic indicator 
totaled $563 million. (Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 
GMT 12 Apr 94) 

</TEXT>

