<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leave UN High Commissioner Headquarters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leave UN High Commissioner Headquarters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2704202294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1847 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2704202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 27 Apr (EFE) -- The 101 Haitians who 
occupied UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) headquarters 
in Santo Domingo on 22 April withdrew from those offices today. 
Lamarre Germain, spokesman for the Haitian group, said they 
voluntarily left after reaching a number of agreements, which he 
did not describe, with UNHCR representative Juan Manuel Castro 
Magluff. 
  The agreements, according to Germain, include the 
acknowledgement that some of his fellow Haitians are political 
refugees, but he did not disclose how many of them would receive 
that status. Germain also said Castro Magluff arranged for all 
of the Haitians to be lodged at a hotel in the high altitude 
area of the Dominican capital and that, in addition, each of 
them were given 500 pesos, the equivalent of $40. Germain said 
the group will remain at the hotel under UN care until each 
person's situation is individually examined. 
  Eleven of the 101 Haitians who occupied the UNHCR 
headquarters were hospitalized and treated for tuberculosis and 
diabetes, among other diseases. The Haitians, 40 men, 20 women, 
and 32 children, occupied the UNHCR headquarters to gain 
political refugee status in the Dominican Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

