<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Police Raid in Raboteau </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Police Raid in Raboteau </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604183694 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] On 22 April, between 23 and 26 persons were 
allegedly killed in the coastal city of Gonaives, northwest of 
Port-au-Prince, by soldiers during a police operation staged at 
dawn in a working-class neighborhood, according to corroborating 
sources. It is the most serious act of collective repression 
committed in a provincial city since the 30 September 1991 coup 
d'etat. The neighborhood [Raboteau], which is the main slum area 
in Gonaives and is famous for its resistance to the Duvalier 
dictatorship in 1983, is reputedly home to numerous partisans of 
President-in-exile Jean-Bertrand Aristide. [passage omitted] 
  The [Justice and Peace] Commission, which considers an 
additional investigation necessary for a final assessment of the 
event, does not rule out the possibility that even more people 
were killed or injured because the attackers fired on homes at a 
level that would compel occupants to exit. The Justice and Peace 
Commission describes the situation in Raboteau as very tragic. 
The populace, men and women of all ages as well as children, had 
to flee the area where gunfire was heard throughout throughout 
the day on 22 April. 
  The Justice and Peace Commission points out that the 22 
April 
raid, carried out by military troops and well-known members of 
the Revolutionary Front for the Promotion and Progress of Haiti, 
followed a first wave of terror in Raboteau after the suspicious 
burning of tires in the streets. In fact, says the Justice and 
Peace Commission, the forces of order were looking for a man 
named Arnault Mtayer, also known as The Cuban, which gave rise 
to searches without warrants and the sacking of several houses 
in Raboteau. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-11432 </DOCNO>
