<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Monde: End Talks, Install Government, Die Together </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Monde: End Talks, Install Government, Die Together </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604220594 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1800 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604220594 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Passage within quotation marks in Creole] </F>
  [Text] The president of the Chamber of Deputies announced 
that the executive power vacuum will probably be filled this 
week. Frantz Robert Monde, reporting on the consultations begun 
last week, indicated that the majority of sectors he met with 
expressed concern about this vacuum. The Chamber of Deputies is 
scheduled to meet soon to choose the constitutional formula 
required within the current context, according to President 
Monde who expressed himself during a news conference today: 
  [Begin Monde recording] At least if the Haitian Armed Forces 
had said no, but President Aristide said yes, we could make them 
meet and see what is negative in this plan. From there, we could 
then manage to find a consensus between the two protagonists of 
the crisis. But, one said no, and because he said no, the 
sanctions must be reinforced. This is an aberration. I therefore 
say that if the sanctions are reinforced, "greeting or not 
greeting your enemy is the same thing; he will eat you up anyway 
for something you did." Close the door on all negotiations, 
install a government, and agree to die together. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

