<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Candidates View Zedillo's Debate Call </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Candidates View Zedillo's Debate Call </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2704035094 Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2704035094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Canal 13 Television Azteca Network 
in Spanish 1300 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Early Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Presidential candidates of small opposition parties 
have termed the debate positive, but demanded that it be more 
open and that all candidates be allowed to participate. 
  [Begin recording] [Alvaro Perez Trevino, presidential 
candidate for the Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution] 
Honestly, no debate has been agreed upon because, in reality, no 
candidate has grabbed the bull by the horns. Now Dr. Zedillo 
has dared to launch this initiative. It is alright because if 
this initiative would not have been presented, no debate would 
occur. 
  [Rafael Aguilar Talamantes, presidential candidate for the 
Cardenist Front for National Reconstruction Party] I will always 
maintain that a debate must be pluralistic and democratic, 
without exclusions. If there are no guarantees that all 
candidates are treated with respect and equality, I would not 
participate in debates of this nature. 
  [Marcela Lombardo Otero, presidential candidate for the 
Popular Socialist Party] If we want to strengthen and expand the 
political-democratic system in the country, it must be done by 
expanding and strengthening the multiparty system, which 
enriches proposals and projects anywhere in the world. 
  [Jorge Gonzalez Torres, presidential candidate for the 
Mexican Green Ecologist Party] We are happy to be part of the 
group of political parties that have been set aside. These 
parties have not been considered for the possibility of debating 
at this level, and the possibility of gaining access to the 
presidency. Well, at least that is what they believe, but the 
reaction of neglected parties will be very powerful. 
  [Pablo Emilio Madero, presidential candidate for the Mexican 
Democratic Party] We are all presidential candidates, there are 
not only three candidates. Therefore, it would be inappropriate 
to hold the debate only amongst three people. 
  [Unidentified reporter] How would you propose that the 
debate 
be held? 
  [Madero] All candidates should be allowed to participate at 
the same time, with the same lighting, the same cameras, the 
same journalists, the same audience, and on conditions of 
equality. This will permit citizens to appreciate what each 
candidate is proposing. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

