<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grand Front Threatens To Leave Constituent Assembly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grand Front Threatens To Leave Constituent Assembly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2604174094 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2349 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2604174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Buenos Aires, 25 Apr (NA) -- The Grand Front 
(FG)'s Constituent Assembly members confirmed today their 
rejection of the Olivos Pact Basic Agreement Nucleus [Nucleo de 
Coincidencias Basicas del Pacto de Olivos] and announced their 
decision to walk out of the Constituent Assembly at voting time 
if the "13-point `package'" agreed upon between the PJ 
[Justicialist Party] and the UCR [Radical Civic Union] on the 
constitutional reform issue "is not opened." 
  The proposal was approved today by 29 of the 31 FG 
Constituent Assembly members elected on 10 April. This was the 
FG's first meeting after the elections. The meeting was held in 
the new FG headquarters at the intersection of Rivadavia Avenue 
and Ayacucho Street. 
  The meeting was chaired by Deputy Carlos "Chacho" Alvarez, 
Deputy Graciela Fernandez Meijide, Deputy Fernando "Pino" 
Solanas, and Neuquen Bishop Monsignor Jaime De Nevares. 
  Among the FG's main leaders also present were former Deputy 
Carlos Auyero, teachers union leader Mary Sanchez, Buenos Aires 
municipal councilman Anibal Ibarra, metalworkers union leader 
Alberto Piccinini, [Communist Party leader] Patricio Etchegaray, 
and Eduardo Barcesat. 
  During the meeting, it was confirmed that Monsignor De 
Nevares will be the FG candidate for Constituent Assembly 
president. De Nevares' candidacy was raised by Solanas. The 
Constituent Assembly is scheduled to reform the Constitution. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

