<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chilean Minister Signs Joint Declaration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chilean Minister Signs Joint Declaration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2704165294 Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network in Spanish 
1000 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2704165294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago Radio Cooperativa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chilean Economy Minister Alvaro Garcia and 
Colombian Foreign Trade Minister Juan Manuel Santos stated that 
the agreements reached during the GATT Uruguay Round represent a 
significant step toward the consolidation of the multilateral 
open trade system. 
  In a joint declaration issued in Cartagena de Indias, 
Colombia, they asserted that the implementation of the free 
trade agreement between Canada, the United States, and Mexico 
opens the possibility of a tighter relationship between the 
North, Central, and South American and Caribbean countries. 
  They also noted that the regional integration programs' 
achievements of the past four years give a new dynamic to the 
processes that link the economies of our region. A similar 
dynamic has generated a series of bilateral agreements between 
the Latin American countries, among which is that signed by the 
governments of Chile and Colombia in late 1993. 
  The declaration later states that the Chilean and Colombian 
Governments have expressed their resolute political will to make 
every possible effort to use this opportunity to materialize the 
desire for Latin American integration and that it spread to the 
rest of the hemisphere. 
  In the Chilean and Colombian economy ministers' opinion, 
free 
access to the markets will promote competition and, hence, the 
efficient development of their respective economies. 
  Finally, the two ministers urged the ECLA [Economic 
Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean] to decidedly 
support the integration efforts with its technical and 
analytical expertise. 

</TEXT>

