<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   MRTA Calls For `Armed Strike' in Jungle Region </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MRTA Calls For `Armed Strike' in Jungle Region </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2604211294 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1548 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2604211294 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Huancayo, Peru, 26 Apr (EFE) -- Official sources 
have reported that the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement 
(MRTA), which has been oficially described as dismantled, has 
called for a two-day "armed strike" in three Peruvian central 
jungle region provinces. A police report released today in 
Huancayo, 415 km southeast of Lima, states that the MRTA, which 
is inspired by Ernesto "Che" Guevara, has called an "armed 
strike" for 28 and 29 April according to announcements painted 
on walls, circulated in bulletins, and written on flags. 
  The three Peruvian central jungle provinces where the "armed 
strike," which is a strike under threat of death, is being 
promoted are Chanchamayo and Satipo in Junin Department, the 
capital of which is Huancayo, and Oxapampa in Pasco Department. 
  An official Defense Ministry communique issued on 21 April 
states that the MRTA attacked a truck carrying soldiers and 
civilians on the Villarrica highway to Oxapampa. They murdered 
three soldiers and 12 civilians and wounded 30 people. Another 
13 people are missing. The communique adds that the Army is 
intensifying operations "to capture the members of the 
narcoterrorist gangs" that operate in the region. [passage 
omitted] 
  Until now the Shining Path was the only organization to have 
called "armed strikes" in different parts of Peru, especially in 
Ayacucho in the South Andean region where this organization was 
born in 1980 and in Lima where the measure always failed despite 
the fact that the transportation sector almost always obeyed the 
strike call. 
  Some analysts believe this action may indicate the union of 
the two subversives organizations, at least in the central 
jungle region. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

