<H3> <TI>   Caldera Names FOGADE, Bank Directors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caldera Names FOGADE, Bank Directors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2804001194 Caracas Union Radio Network in Spanish 1600 GMT 
27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2804001194 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Union Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Vicente Briceno from the "Union Radio Noticias" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] President Rafael Caldera has sworn in new directors 
for FOGADE [Deposit Guarantee and Banking Protection Fund] and 
the General Bank Superintendency--Norys Aguirre and Tesalio 
Cadenas, respectively. After they were sworn in, both officers 
ruled out controls on foreign exchange. They also said they 
intend to evaluate the assistance given to banks as well as the 
proposals made by Gustavo Roosen, special commissioner for 
financial reforms. 
  FOGADE Director Norys Aguirre stressed her institution's 
duty 
to restore confidence in the financial system, and she said that 
currently the state is the greatest FOGADE contributor. She 
referred to strategies by the leadership of FOGADE by announcing 
reforms to the law that created this fund. 
  [Begin Aguirre recording] Basically there are two 
strategies. 
One is the short-term strategy, and this is the immediate 
solution to the current banking crisis. The long-term strategy 
deals with reforms, and if these are needed I will be the first 
person to propose them, as I have done up to now, through 
Congress to the government, in due course. I am not afraid to 
make changes. If a complete FOGADE reorganization is needed, 
this will be done. [end recording] 
  For his part, Tesalio Cadenas admitted that the General Bank 
Superintendency had faults that failed to prevent greater 
control--in other words, stricter control--of the Venezuelan 
financial system. 

</TEXT>

