<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Economic Minister Condemns Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Economic Minister Condemns Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2604201394 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2604201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 26 April, Ernesto Melendez, Cuban minister of 
Foreign Investment and Economic Cooperation, condemned the U.S. 
blockade at the 25th meeting of the Economic Commission for 
Latin America and the Caribbean being held in Cartagena, 
Colombia. 
  Melendez also condemned U.S. pressure on countries in the 
region to prevent Cuba from joining regional integration 
organizations in specific sectors such as tourism. In his 
address, Melendez stressed the deplorable health indexes of the 
continent, which have been aggravated by the imposed economic 
models. Regarding these models of commercial opening, complete 
privatization, and unregulated foreign investment, Melendez 
pointed out that 270 million people living in poverty is too 
high a figure for a population of 450 million people, in 
addition to distressing indexes of unemployment, infant 
mortality, and education, which brings to mind an endemic 
adjustment rather than a true recovery. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

